{"slug":"competitor-nominations","graph":"companies","title":"Who else orbits the red-team cluster","sub":"14 flagged rivals vote; the graph nominates the rest","headline":"The 14 flagged competitors' fused vote names <strong>Lasso Security, Zenity, Noma Security</strong> as rival-shaped but never flagged, and puts UiPath at the top of the buyer-side shortlist — 13/20 prospects and 8/10 rivals survive adding the 71 unverified edges.","prose":{"intro":"<p>We hand-flagged 14 companies as competitors. Two business questions follow: which <em>buyers</em> does the network place in the same orbit as that red-team cluster (a prospecting shortlist), and which un-flagged startups or labs does it treat as one of the pack — rivals the flag list may have missed?</p>","how":"<p>This is vertex nomination — recommendation from examples, the way a search engine takes a few example results and finds more like them. Every company gets a vector from the graph's verified wiring alone (an adjacency spectral embedding, the graph analogue of a word embedding), and the 14 flagged competitors act as the query. The sanity check comes first, and it fails in an instructive way: the seeds are <em>not</em> a tight cluster — their mean pairwise distance is 1.33× the market average, more spread than 88% of random same-sized subsets. That is exactly why we don't average the seeds into one centroid (the query point would land in empty space between them). Instead each seed votes independently: it ranks all 157 candidates by distance, and the 14 ranked lists are fused two ways — Borda count (points for placing high on each list) and reciprocal-rank fusion (the metasearch trick that rewards top placements). The two fusions agree on 16 of their top-20; that overlap is the consensus set colored on the map. The “edges” column shows how much verified wiring supports each nomination — a rank built on 2 edges is a lead, not a verdict.</p>","method":"<p>Vertex nomination via adjacency spectral embedding (Fishkind, Lyzinski, Pao, Chen &amp; Priebe, <em>Vertex nomination schemes for membership prediction</em>, Ann. Appl. Stat. 2015). ASE of the binarized undirected company graph, verified edges only (417 unique pairs from 421 verified records; diagonal augmentation; Zhu–Ghodsi elbow picked d=4; svd_seed=0). The graph is disconnected — 17 companies have no verified edge, embed at exactly the origin, and are excluded from the candidate pool as artifacts. Per-seed Euclidean distance ranks are fused by Borda count and by reciprocal-rank fusion (Cormack, Clarke &amp; Büttcher, SIGIR 2009; k=60), ties broken lexicographically. Tightness null: 1000 random seed-sized subsets of embedded companies. Sensitivity: the pipeline re-run on all 485 unique pairs including unverified edges, same candidate pool; a row “survives” if it stays in its table.</p>"},"caveat":"All the seeds live in one vertical (security-eval-vendor), so nomination partly re-reads vertical structure — treat the buyer-side list as “wired into the red-team world”, not intent to buy. Face-validity cuts both ways: the rivals table surfaces real unflagged security vendors, but AoC's own node ranks only #89 of 157 — with 2 verified edges the method can't see us either. Thin nominations (1–3 edges) rest on one or two ties; check the edges column. Note who is missing: bank-fintech barely registers — the graph puts banks nowhere near the red-team cluster yet.","inputs":{"companies":{"nodes":188,"edges":492}},"data":{"tightness":{"seed_mean":0.547,"market_mean":0.411,"ratio":1.331,"null_pctile":0.877},"prospects":[{"id":"uipath","label":"UiPath","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":2,"rrf":6,"deg":2,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"VP of Automation / Chief Automation Officer (owns agent governance and reliability)"},{"id":"servicenow","label":"ServiceNow","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":5,"rrf":8,"deg":5,"intensity":5,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Trust & Risk Officer / VP AI Governance (owns the AI Control Tower)"},{"id":"palantir","label":"Palantir","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":6,"rrf":5,"deg":2,"intensity":5,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Head of AI / CISO (and forward-deployed engineering leadership owning AIP deployments)"},{"id":"abridge","label":"Abridge","vertical":"healthcare","borda":9,"rrf":14,"deg":4,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Medical Information Officer (CMIO) / VP Clinical AI"},{"id":"sap","label":"SAP","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":12,"rrf":17,"deg":3,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief AI Officer / Head of AI Ethics & Trust"},{"id":"regard","label":"Regard","vertical":"healthcare","borda":14,"rrf":13,"deg":3,"intensity":3,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Medical Officer / VP of Clinical Informatics"},{"id":"suki","label":"Suki","vertical":"healthcare","borda":18,"rrf":18,"deg":4,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Medical Information Officer (CMIO) / VP Clinical Informatics"},{"id":"groq","label":"Groq","vertical":"infra platform","borda":19,"rrf":28,"deg":4,"intensity":4,"survives":false,"flag":"drops with unverified edges","persona":"VP Engineering / Head of AI"},{"id":"adobe","label":"Adobe","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":20,"rrf":26,"deg":2,"intensity":3,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Trust Officer / VP Responsible AI"},{"id":"atlassian","label":"Atlassian","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":21,"rrf":29,"deg":2,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Head of Trust / CISO"},{"id":"ambience-healthcare","label":"Ambience Healthcare","vertical":"healthcare","borda":25,"rrf":27,"deg":9,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Medical Information Officer (CMIO) / VP of Coding & CDI Compliance"},{"id":"workday","label":"Workday","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":26,"rrf":32,"deg":6,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Trust Officer / VP 